Yes. In a PowerShell script, override **only for that session/process** by setting `$env:JAVA_HOME` and prepending the JDK 21 `bin` folder to `$env:PATH`, then run Dependency-Check **in the same script**. PowerShell environment variables are process-scoped by default in the session, and child processes inherit them. Also, `Start-Process` inherits the current process environment unless you override it. ([Microsoft Learn][1])

Use this:

```powershell
$jdkHome = 'D:\Java\jdk-21.0.10'
$dcBat   = 'C:\Tools\dependency-check\dependency-check-12.2.0\bin\dependency-check.bat'

# Override only for this PowerShell session
$env:JAVA_HOME = $jdkHome
$env:PATH = "$jdkHome\bin;$env:PATH"

# Verify what this session will use
Write-Host "JAVA_HOME = $env:JAVA_HOME"
Get-Command java | Select-Object Source
java -version

# Run Dependency-Check in the same session
& $dcBat `
  --version
```

If you want the full scan:

```powershell
$jdkHome   = 'D:\Java\jdk-21.0.10'
$dcBat     = 'C:\Tools\dependency-check\dependency-check-12.2.0\bin\dependency-check.bat'
$dataDir   = 'C:\Tools\dependency-check-data'
$reportDir = 'C:\temp\odc-report'
$scanPath  = 'D:\YourRepo'

$env:JAVA_HOME = $jdkHome
$env:PATH = "$jdkHome\bin;$env:PATH"

New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force -Path $reportDir | Out-Null

Write-Host "Using java from:"
Get-Command java | Select-Object Source
java -version

& $dcBat `
  --project "debug-test" `
  --scan $scanPath `
  --out $reportDir `
  --data $dataDir `
  --noupdate `
  --disableKnownExploited `
  --disableHostedSuppressions `
  --disableRetireJS `
  --disableVersionCheck `
  --log "$reportDir\odc.log"

if ($LASTEXITCODE -ne 0) {
  Get-Content "$reportDir\odc.log" -Tail 200
  exit $LASTEXITCODE
}
```

If you want to force it even harder, call Java by full path for verification:

```powershell
& 'D:\Java\jdk-21.0.10\bin\java.exe' -version
```

That works because specifying a full path bypasses normal command lookup precedence. ([Microsoft Learn][2])

If you want this every time you open PowerShell, put the two lines below in your PowerShell profile:

```powershell
$env:JAVA_HOME = 'D:\Java\jdk-21.0.10'
$env:PATH = "$env:JAVA_HOME\bin;$env:PATH"
```

PowerShell profiles are the standard place to apply session startup customizations. ([Microsoft Learn][3])

The one thing to remember is: changing `JAVA_HOME` alone is often not enough for `java -version`; the active `java.exe` comes from the current `PATH`, so you should set both. Microsoft’s Java-on-Windows guidance also shows `JAVA_HOME` plus `%JAVA_HOME%\bin` in `Path`. ([Microsoft Learn][4])

